					Re: Windows 7 Organization / Opimization
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1832377">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				Where as your OS drive is always adding and removing temp files based on current operational needs I imagine that is the primary cause of fragmenting.
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Yes, that's exactly right.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				 I know SSDs never need and should never be defraged
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>and that's because SSD's have limited read write cycles.  <br />
<br />
which a Defrag will use up relatively fast.  (as it does the same thing, move sections of files to temporary locations, then move them to another location that may or may not also be temporary in order to move them to another location.)  While at the same time, performance losses from fragmented files are considerably lessened, because you don't have a physical &quot;head&quot; that has to move from position to position.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
